node.title: An independent elastoplasticity (CamClay) model for soil mechanics
node.bodyText:
I am writing to inform you of my recent development of an AD constitutive material with applications in soil mechanics, specifically the CamClay model. After successfully testing this code in the C++ library Deal.II, I have decided to develop the AD version in MOOSE to add additional features without the need for derivatives and Jacobians.
Despite attempting to fit the model into different subclasses of MOOSE to minimize manipulation, my first attempt using the ADGeneralizedRadialReturnMapping was unsuccessful due to its tie to the elasticity tensor, which conflicts with CamClay's unique elasticity tensor update. As a result, I have tried directly implementing the CamClay model as an ADStrainIncrementBasedStressUpdate. However, although I have successfully compiled the code, it does not converge for unknown reasons. I am particularly confused by the interdependencies of parameters, such as _stress[_qp], _incremental_strain[_qp], and others that must be provided.
To diagnose the issue, I have run several tests and have concluded that the problem occurs in the first step of the analysis before entering the plastic region. I suspect that the inconsistency of the initial stress and strain may be at fault. To elaborate, the CamClay model begins with an initial confining pressure (e.g., -100kPa) and then applies a deviatoric stress on top of a biaxial plain strain sample from the top.
If you have any recommendations or advice on how to resolve this issue or any potential oversights, please do not hesitate to let me know. I appreciate any help and am eager to resolve this issue as soon as possible.
Mahyar

node.title: Problem updating kernels for current MOOSE
node.bodyText:
Hello all,
I have a problem regarding the update of my custom kernels to the newest syntax. After updating MOOSE using the standard way from the tutorial, I ran into the problem that parts of the code date back to before 2020, and as I have found the syntax was changed in April 2020 (https://mooseframework.inl.gov/releases/moose/2021-09-15/newsletter/2020_04.html).
I have uploaded the kernels in question on my Github (https://github.com/mfitzka/phoenixpublic) under h kernels old/updated and C kernels old/updated.
If anyone could take a look at the files (especially CoupledCureTimeDerivative and DCPDnonDgeneralPT since they are my main problem at the moment) it would be very much appreciated.

Hello
It should be validParams not validParms
in your header
   static InputParameters validParms(const InputParameters & parameters);

Guillaume

In the header
You have
   static InputParameters validParams(const InputParameters & parameters);

It should be:
  static InputParameters validParams();

In the source
You have:
    template<>
    InputParameters
    CoupledCureTimeDerivative::validParams()
   {

It should be:
InputParameters
CoupledCureTimeDerivative::validParams()
{

node.title: How MOOSE computes eigen strain?
node.bodyText:
Hello,
From tensor mechanics module, it is possible to add eigenstrain to a linear elastic system (https://mooseframework.inl.gov/modules/tensor_mechanics/plug_n_play.html#qu2006fundamentals).
ADComputeFiniteStrainElasticStress can calculate stress due to finite strain including eigen strain.
Now $\varepsilon_{total} = \varepsilon_{eigen} + \varepsilon_{mechanical}$
ADComputeFiniteStrainElasticStress calculates  $\varepsilon_{mechanical}$ using Eulerian-Almansi finite strain tensor as $\varepsilon_{mechanical} = \frac{1}{2} (I - (\boldsymbol{F}.\boldsymbol{F}^{T})^{-1} )$.   (is it correct?)
How MOOSE calculates the total stress in this case? as hooks law is not valied for eigen strain so it couldn't be $\sigma = C. (\varepsilon_{eigen} + \varepsilon_{mechanical})$? Using green's function? how? Can you please explain the theory behind it?
Thank you.

Hello
There's some documentation on eigenstrain here
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/moose/source/materials/ComputeEigenstrain.html
The references cited should explain the theory in more details
Guillaume

Hello,
Thanks. I already checked the references. Is it possible to briefly summarize how MOOSE deals with eigenstrain? I am confused how MOOSE handles finite strain and eigen strain at the same time to compute stress and strain energy.
For instance using fourier integral-

Or Using Green function -
@dschwen @recuero

The tensor mechanics system you are looking at uses additive decomposition of the total incremental strain.
The total incremental strain e_total = e_mechanical + e_eigenstrain and e_mechanical = e_elastic + e_plastic.
The stress sigma = C * e_elastic.

Hello,
Does that mean, in MOOSE, the nodal point displacement gives the deformation gradient. From where we can calculate the total strain. Then , elastic strain = total strain - inputed eigen strain.
Then calculate the sigma = c * elastic strain ?

Hello
Indeed this interface kernel specifies h, the heat transfer coefficient between the solid and the fluid. It doesnt say you cant model fluid. It's just fixing (well it can still vary, it's a material property) the heat transfer coefficient between the two adjacent cells at the interface.
But you are right that this encapsulates the boundary layer behavior. We have not implemented any boundary layer treatment save for this interface kernel, which is very simplified treatment for heat transfer.
Guillaume

Is it possible to do this without using the conjugate heat transfer kernel?
Jake

Currently not without new code. However MOOSE is designed to be easy to contribute to. What you need to add would fit under an interface kernel, and there's nothing else you need to worry about to get compatibility with everything else in the module

@j-bowhay the reason you are seeing no conduction is because you are using a CombinerGenerator. This class makes no attempts to stitch the meshes together, so the elements on the different mesh blocks do not form neighbor connections with the other mesh blocks. You could use a CartesianMeshGenerator or one GeneratedMeshGenerator and then a couple SubdomainBoundingBoxGenerators etc. Even a couple StitchedMeshGenerators but I wouldn't recommend that for this simple of a geometry.
Because elements don't form neighbor connections with the neighboring mesh blocks, the FV system thinks the mesh interfaces are actually external boundaries with neither flux nor Dirichlet boundaries specified and consequently treats those boundaries as natural boundaries (e.g. no flux)

node.title: Eulerian-Eulerian (2-Phase) kernals
node.bodyText:
Hi all,
Is it possible to model an Eulerian-Eulerian (gas-liquid) fluid flow in MOOSE? What kind of kernels would I look towards?

Hello
No we do not have two phase (gas-liquid) fluid flow in MOOSE.
Are you doing CFD or 1D thermal hydraulics? For the latter you can request access to RELAP-7.
For CFD you could develop your own set of kernels and we would be interested in this contribution
Guillaume

I am doing CFD with OPENMC and MOOSE wrapped by Cardinal. I am interested in modeling the production and removal of xenon-135 by sparging helium bubbles. This was easily accomplished in ANSYS Fluent, but lacked the coupling of neutronics and thermals.
Now, I want to take my work a step further by incorporating neutronics, thermal, and fluid flow into this topic. My draft "idea" is a simple 2-D closed loop with the core on one side and components on the opposing side. A momentum source term that acts as a pump and a sink term for the heat exchanger. Xenon-135 will be a source term in the continuity equation, which is coupled with neutronics from OPENMC.
I am leaning towards the ladder since it may also fulfill my dissertation topic. However, I have a few gaps in my understanding of MOOSE and Bubble-bubble CFD modeling that I need to fulfill prior to implementation.
-Thanks

Sounds good. Please let us know if you run into any issue implementing or have any questions.
You may consider a simple drift flux model as a first step.

I am running a simulation that involves a dynamical equation (magnetic Landau-Lifshitz-Gilbert equation) and an auxiliary Poisson equation to solve for the magnetostatic potential. As the time scale for the potential can be different (longer) than that of the dynamical equation, I am using a MultiApp to solve for the Poisson equation. It works, but I noticed some quirks: (1) I have to declare the potential (phi) a nonlinear variable in the parent - I cannot declare it an AuxVariable in the parent because it has to be a nonlinear variable in the MultiApp and it seems like transferring a nonlinear variable in the parent to an Aux in the MultiApp does not work; (2) as a consequence I have to define phi a nonlinear variable in the parent . But because phi lives in more blocks than the dynamical variables, I have to define Kernels on those blocks in the parent. Because there is nothing to be done on phi in the parent, I use NullKernel; (3) it appears that the code crashes (PETSc errors - matrix blocks are not defined or zero) unless I define a boundary condition on phi in the parent. Because I don't do anything on phi I just wrote a NullBC that does nothing (similar to NullKernel) but now it all works.
Am I missing something here? It all would seem a lot simpler if I could transfer the nonlinear variable phi to an Aux variable in the MultiApp.
Thanks,
Olle
